    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1962-10-29T02:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1962-10-29T02:30:00-05:00" n="188"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d188">
                <head>188. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in India</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d188fn0">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 791.5/10-2962. Secret; Niact; Limit Distribution. Repeated to London
                        and Karachi.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>New Delhi</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1962-10-29T13:00:00+05:30">October 29, 1962, 1 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1443. Dept’s telegram 1687.<note n="1" xml:id="d188fn1">
                        <ref target="#d187">Document 187</ref>.</note> Ambassador saw
                        <persName>Nehru</persName> just before noon to deliver President’s letter.
                        <persName>Nehru</persName> made definite request for US military
                    assistance.</p>
                <p>Ambassador and <gloss target="#t_DCM1">DCM</gloss> later saw <persName
                        corresp="#p_MVKK1">Menon</persName> briefly at latter’s request. <persName
                        corresp="#p_MVKK1">Menon</persName> reaffirmed request for assistance and
                    said list of requirements would be delivered to Embassy tonight or
                        tomorrow.<note n="2" xml:id="d188fn2">See <ref target="#d192">Document
                            192</ref>. The initial U.S. response to the Indian requests was outlined
                        in an October 31 memorandum from <persName corresp="#p_BWP1">William
                            Bundy</persName> to <persName corresp="#p_MNRS1">McNamara</persName>.
                        (Washington National Records Center, <gloss target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 330,
                        OSD Files: <gloss target="#t_FRC1">FRC</gloss> 66 A 3542, India, 091.3
                            <gloss target="#t_MSP1">MSP</gloss>, 29 Oct 62)</note> Stressed urgent
                    need for automatic weapons and long-range mortars.</p>
                <p>Ambassador is now seeing Foreign Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DMJ1"
                        >Desai</persName> and will draft full and important telegram on these
                    conversations within next hour.<note n="3" xml:id="d188fn3">
                        <persName corresp="#p_GJK1">Galbraith</persName>’s account of his
                        conversations with <persName>Nehru</persName> and <persName
                            corresp="#p_MVKK1">Menon</persName> indicates that <persName
                            corresp="#p_MVKK1">Menon</persName> attempted to take credit for
                        arranging for military aid from the United States by asking to meet with
                            <persName corresp="#p_GJK1">Galbraith</persName> before <persName
                            corresp="#p_GJK1">Galbraith</persName> met with
                            <persName>Nehru</persName>. <persName corresp="#p_GJK1"
                            >Galbraith</persName> responded that he had to deliver the President’s
                        letter to the Prime Minister before he could meet with <persName
                            corresp="#p_MVKK1">Menon</persName>. <persName>Nehru</persName> then
                        made the request for military assistance. (Telegram 1448 from New Delhi,
                        October 29; Department of State, Central Files, 791.5/10-2962)</note>
                </p>
                <p>Most important that Department’s comments to press stress that request for US
                    military assistance was made by Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_NJ1"
                        >Nehru</persName> personally. Embassy taking same line here with press.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="strong">
                            <persName corresp="#p_GJK1">Galbraith</persName>
                        </hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
